<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en-US">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Earth Tweets</title>
  <%- css('style') %>
</head>
<body>

<div class="wrapper">
  <div id="container"></div>

  <div id="title">Earth Tweets</div>

  <div id="currentInfo">
    <p class="byline"><small>by <a href="http://github.com/ngoldman">ngoldman</a></small></p>

    <p>This is a mashup of the Google Data Arts Team's WebGL Globe project and the Twitter Streaming API. A random sampling of live data is piped in from Twitter to a <a href="http://nodejs.org/">Node.js</a> server, then sent to the browser using a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WebSocket">WebSocket</a> connection and mapped onto a WebGL map of the planet using <a href="http://mrdoob.github.com/three.js/">Three.js</a>.</p>

    <p>
      <strong>Click</strong> on the planet and <strong>drag around</strong>.
      Use <strong>mousewheel</strong> or <strong>up</strong> and
      <strong>down</strong> arrows to zoom.
    </p>

    <p>
      <label class="checkbox">
        <input id="toggle-panning" type="checkbox" checked="checked"> Pan to new tweets
      </label>
    </p>

    <p>
      <button id="toggle-stream" class="btn btn-danger btn-block" disabled="disabled">
        <i class="icon-play icon-white"></i> Start streaming live data
      </button>
    </p>

    <input id="filter" type="text" placeholder="filter results by search term">
  </div>

  <div id="info">
    Based on <a href="http://www.chromeexperiments.com/globe" target="_blank">WebGL Globe</a> by the Google Data Arts Team
    <span class="bull">&bull;</span>
    Data acquired from <a href="https://dev.twitter.com/docs/streaming-apis" target="_blank">Twitter Streaming API</a>
    <span class="bull">&bull;</span>
    <a href="http://github.com/ngoldman/earth-tweets">View Source</a> on Github
  </div>
</div>

<script src="/socket.io/socket.io.js"></script>
<script src="http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?sensor=false"></script>
<%- js('client') %>

</body>
</html>
